Input.threadtitle: The Doppler Shift - why is there a 'minus' sign on the blackboard?
Input.posts:

(And thereby answer the question: why is there a 'minus' sign on the blackboard, and NOT on this page?) ...' I was able to crank out the formula as suggested, but am having difficulty understanding why the minus sign is in the result. (which is the real point of the question). Searching other online resources gives no joy either. Thanks for any thoughts, Bill

Input.threadtitle: The magnetic field of Cen X-3.
Input.posts:
Since a neutron star is made entirely of neutrons, how can it have a magnetic field ? Isn't a magnetic field something that is produced by charged particles moving around ? Are there charged particles in a neutron star ?
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
That's a fantastic question, and it's one that is still in debate among astrophysicists. Models of neutron stars generally include some matter on the outer shell and 'atmosphere' of the star that is composed of ions and an electron gas (see the picture here ). Observationally we know that neutron stars have large magnetic fields (this is what creates the pulsars we see), but it is uncertain how they appear. This paper seems to suggest that the field may come from differential rotation in the final stages of core-collapse supernovae as a possible source.
Instructor's post : That's a fantastic question, and it's one that is still in debate among astrophysicists. Input.threadtitle: End of lecture 7 - why cm?
Input.posts:
At the end of lecture 7, the professor converts the distance in light years to Cen X3 to centimeters. (He's done this for large distances in other lectures as well.) Why use such a small unit of measure for such large distances?
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
In astronomy, we use a system of measurements referred to as c-g-s, which stands for centimeter-gram-seconds. All of the units we use are based off of those values (e.g. erg for energy and dyne for force). I know it may seem a bit counter intuitive to use such small units for such large objects, but that is just the convention that we use.
Instructor's post : In astronomy, we use a system of measurements referred to as c-g-s, which stands for centimeter-gram-seconds. Title: Linking forum posts - analyze-6-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Lecture 5-2: Kepler's Third law
Input.posts:
I think it is important to use the more general form of Kepler's 3rd law when dealing with binary star systems because, unlike star-planet systems the ratio of the less massive component to the more massive is often not >> 1.0. In the more general case in which the smaller mass is a significant, $$\frac{P^2} {a^3} = \frac{4 {\pi}^2} {G(M+m)}$$ where $$P$$ is the period of orbit $$a$$ is the length of the semi-major axis (= radius for circular orbits) $$M$$ is the larger mass, and $$m$$ is the smaller mass In the case of Cen X-3, the less massive component is more than 5% of the mass of the more massive and, therefore, is significant. Brad Walter

Title: Linking forum posts - analyze-6-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Cen X-3 Exosat questions
Input.posts:
Why is Cen X-3's Exosat light curve so slow, sloppy, and complex coming out of eclipse versus going into eclipse? If there is a Roche lobe feeding an accretion disk, my gut feeling would have been that the light curve might have been more abrupt coming out of eclipse than entering eclipse, though I'm not sure why. I guess I have no idea of the phase relationship between the neutron star and the Roche lobe. The amount of time to transition into eclipse seems to be something like 3000 seconds. Tens of thousands of times longer than for the neutron star itself. Is this the accretion disk going into eclipse? Or the xrays passing through the outer atmosphere of the companion star but attenuated? The transition does seem to have steps in it: layers of the atmosphere? There is a small pulsar component even during eclipse: absorption by and re-emission from a halo around the companion star?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
This observation is a treasure trove of data concerning the atmosphere of the companion star. The complication is that everything is quite variable: the atmosphere of the companion is very tenuous, Cen X-3 is very erratic from second to second. Massive x-ray binaries tend not to have extensive accretion disks, being powered more by stellar winds instead. But that is a complication too. You are asking the right questions, for sure!

Input.threadtitle: URCA - from The world of David Darling
Input.posts:
Sharing a short explanation of URCA :- A cycle of nuclear reactions in which a nucleus loses energy by first absorbing an electron and then reemitting a beta particle (a high-speed electron) plus a neutrino-antineutrino pair. It is an important process in pre-supernova stars because, by cooling and decreasing the pressure in the star's core, it renders the core unable to support the weight of the overlying layers. These layers collapse onto the core and subsequently rebound and escape in the supernova explosion. 'Urca' is not an acronym but the name of a casino in Rio de Janeiro at which George Gamow commented to the Brazilian astrophysicist and art critic Mario Schenberg (1914-1990) (who first pointed out the importance of neutrino emission in supernovae to Gamow): 'the energy disappears in the nucleus of the supernova as quickly as the money disappeared at that roulette table.' The process was dramatically confirmed by Supernova 1987A whose observation coincided with a burst of 11 neutrinos, detected by the the Super-Kamiokande in Japan, and a further eight registered independently by a detector in Ohio.

Input.threadtitle: Lost in lecture 5
Input.posts:
About 2 minutes in, Prof. Matilsky says that the frequencies are changing smoothly, with a period of 2.09 days. I don't actually see that in the DS9 Power Spectrum window... how can you tell the frequency is changing smoothly, when the zoom tool looks so jaggedy? How do you get from frequency periods of 4 seconds and change in the region he zoomed in on to the 2.09 day higher level period?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Recall that here we are looking at the power spectrum, so this shows us how prevalent (or powerful) certain frequencies are in the spectrum. Even though the power spectrum shows jagged peaks around 0.207 Hz, this just shows that there is variation in the exact frequency of peaks in the actual light curve spectrum. We know that Cen X-3 is eclipsed every 2.09 days, but this period is distinct from the period of oscillations we see in the un-eclipsed spectrum.

Input.posts:
In Lecture 4 Dr Matilsky says 'Because these compact objects are small and have intense gravitational fields, they can accelerate materials to very high speeds. When the accelerated material collides, is it the star or the neighboring gas that heats up?
Upvotes:

Instructor's Post
